'''Alessandro Liborio "Al" Madrigal''' (born July 4, 1971<ref name=TheCaptain>[http://www.cbs.com/primetime/the_captain/bio/al_madrigal/bio.php "'Welcome to The Captain,' Al Madrigal bio," CBS.com]</ref>) is an [[United States|American]] [[stand-up comedian]] and [[actor]]. He is a regular correspondent on ''[[The Daily Show with Jon Stewart]]''. He previously co-starred in the [[CBS]] prime-time situation comedies ''[[Gary Unmarried]]'' with [[Jay Mohr]] and ''[[Welcome to The Captain]]''<ref name=TheCaptain /> with [[Fran Kranz]].  He was a regular sketch performer on ''[[The Late Late Show]]''<ref>{{IMDb name|1371339}}</ref> with [[Craig Ferguson]] and has also appeared on ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]''. He also starred on NBC's ''[[About a Boy (TV series)|About A Boy]]'' which premiered in February 2014.

==Early life==
A native of [[San Francisco, California]], Madrigal grew up in the city's [[Sunset District, San Francisco, California|Inner Sunset District]], where his neighbors included future comedians [[Mike Pritchard]], [[Margaret Cho]] and the Meehan Brothers. His father is of [[Mexico|Mexican heritage]] while his mother is of [[Sicilian people|Sicilian heritage]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Al-Madrigal-to-play-the-Punch-Line-3271245.php |title=Al Madrigal to play the Punch Line |author=Tamara Straus |publisher=San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate=2013-06-25 |date=March 4, 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://twitter.com/almadrigal/status/413468097345880065 Twitter]</ref> He attended [[St. Ignatius College Preparatory]] High School where he was [[salutatorian]] for the class of 1989. He then attended the [[University of San Francisco]], but left the school two credits shy of receiving a degree. Madrigal worked for 10 years in a human resources staffing agency run by his family. In 1998, he decided to pursue a full-time career in comedy.<ref>[http://www.latinostandup.com/pages/almad.html “Al Madrigal,” LatinoStandup.com]</ref>

==Career==
Madrigal appeared in San Francisco's [[comedy club]]s, both as a solo performer and as a member of the sketch group Fresh Robots, which he co-founded. In 2002, he enjoyed his first major exposure in two comedy festivals: Sketchfest in San Francisco, as part of Fresh Robots,<ref>[http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/chronicle/archive/2002/01/03/DD29268.DTL&type=printable "Jokers Run Wild," January 3, 2002]</ref> and the "New Faces" showcase of the Just for Laughs Festival in [[Montreal]].<ref name=BG>[http://www.boston.com/ae/theater_arts/articles/2008/06/27/hes_starting_over____again/ "He's Starting Over – Again," ''The Boston Globe'', June 27, 2008]</ref>

In 2003, Madrigal successfully auditioned for a starring role on ''The Ortegas'', a comedy series for the [[Fox Network]]. The series, which was based on the [[BBC]] comedy ''[[The Kumars at No. 42]]'', cast Madrigal as the son of a [[Mexican American]] family in California who hosts a TV talk show from a studio he operates in the backyard of his parents' home.<ref>[http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117892338?refCatId=1681 "Al Madrigal: 'The Ortegas'" ''Variety'', September 11, 2003]</ref> However, the network dropped the series from its schedule before broadcasting any of its six filmed episodes.<ref>[http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=980CE3D7133CF935A35753C1A9659C8B63 "Fox Drops 'The Ortegas' but Insists the Show Has Not Been Canceled," ''The New York Times'', October 6, 2003]</ref>

Comedy Central featured his stand up in their animated series [[Shorties Watchin' Shorties]]. Madrigal won a jury award in 2004 for best stand-up comedian at the [[U.S. Comedy Arts Festival]] in [[Aspen, Colorado]]. After winning the award, he signed a talent holding deal with [[CBS]].<ref>[http://web.archive.org/web/20070808113343/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/search/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1000797090 "Comedy ice," ''The Hollywood Reporter'', March 1, 2006]</ref> However, he would not appear on CBS until January 2008, when he was cast as a building attendant named Jesus (pronounced “Jee-sus”) in the CBS comedy ''[[Welcome to The Captain]]''.<ref>[http://www.newsday.com/entertainment/tv/ny-ettel0204,0,1956874.story?track=rss "'The Captain' not welcome on my television," ''Newsday'', February 4, 2008]{{dead link|date=July 2011}}</ref> The series was cancelled after five episodes.<ref>[http://tvseriesfinale.com/tv-show/cbs-announces-their-2008-09-schedule-whos-been-cancelled/ "CBS Announces Their 2008-09 Schedule. Who's Been Cancelled?" TVSeriesFinale.com]</ref>

Madrigal was the star of a 2005 [[Comedy Central]] special, and has been a guest on ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]'' and ''[[The Late Late Show with Craig Ferguson]]''. He co-starred in the CBS series ''[[Gary Unmarried]]'' (originally titled ''Project Gary''), which debuted on CBS in September 2008.<ref name=BG /> He appeared on ''[[The Tonight Show]]'' with [[Conan O'Brien]] on July 8, 2009.<ref>[http://www.tonightshowwithconanobrien.com/video/clips/al-madrigal-070809/1133907/]{{dead link|date=July 2011}}</ref> He appeared again on Conan's new TBS Show ''[[Conan (talk show)|Conan]]'' on May 10, 2011.<ref>[http://teamcoco.com/video/10289/comedian-al-madrigal-knows-how-to-pick-em Comedian Al Madrigal Knows How To Pick Em - Video @ Teamcoco.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> It was announced on May 17, 2011, that he would be joining ''[[The Daily Show with Jon Stewart]]''. On March 14, 2013, it was announced that Al would be joining NBC's [[About a Boy (TV series)|About A Boy]].<ref>http://www.deadline.com/2013/03/al-madrigal-boards-about-a-boy-delirium-adds-a-friend-reign-casts-nastradamus/</ref>

===All Things Comedy===
In 2012, Madrigal and comedian [[Bill Burr]] founded [[All Things Comedy]], a comedy podcast network and artist cooperative.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Espinoza|first1=Russ|title=New Model for a Funny Business|url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/arts/2015-03-13/new-model-for-a-funny-business/|website=The Austin Chronicle|publisher=Austin Chronicle Corp.|accessdate=15 May 2015}}</ref> Madrigal and Burr started the network as a way to help comedians maintain full ownership of their work.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Espinoza|first1=Russ|title=New Model for a Funny Business|url=(http://www.austinchronicle.com/arts/2015-03-13/new-model-for-a-funny-business/)|website=The Austin Chronicle|publisher=Austin Chronicle Corp.|accessdate=15 May 2015}}</ref>  The network hosts over 50 podcasts and garners nearly 5 million listeners per month.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McGlynn|first1=Katia|title=5 Things Comedians Can Learn from Bill Burr, Al Madrigal and the Power of All Things Comedy|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/03/18/all-things-comedy_n_6896750.html|website=Huffington Post|publisher=TheHuffingtonPost.com, Inc.|accessdate=15 May 2015}}</ref> 

At [[South by Southwest|South by Southwest 2015]], Madrigal, Burr, and comedian [[Doug Benson]] spoke on the “Owning Your Work: The Future of All Things Comedy” panel, where they “discussed the ins and outs of their operation and how they are working to help comics carve out their own paths in show business and avoid traditional gatekeepers.”<ref>{{cite web|last1=McGlynn|first1=Katia|title=5 Things Comedians Can Learn From Bill Burr, Al Madrigal and the Power of All Things Comedy|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/03/18/all-things-comedy_n_6896750.html|website=The Huffington Post|publisher=TheHuffingtonPost.com, Inc.|accessdate=15 May 2015}}</ref> 

From 2010-2014, he co-hosted a podcast called “Minivan Men” with comedians Maz Jobrani, Aaron Aryanpur, and Chris Spencer, in which they discussed marriage, parenting, and domestic issues.<ref>{{cite web|last1=N/A|first1=N/A|title=Minivan Men|url=http://allthingscomedy.com/channels/1/minivan-men|website=All Things Comedy|publisher=All Things Comedy|accessdate=15 May 2015}}</ref>

Madrigal and Burr host the “All Things Comedy Live Podcast,” which streams monthly. The podcast has featured comics including [[Sinbad (comedian)|Sinbad]], [[Nick Thune]], Felipe Esparza, Doug Benson, [[Pete Holmes]], [[Ian Edwards (comedian)|Ian Edwards]], and [[Fred Stoller]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=N/A|first1=N/A|title=All Things Comedy Live Podcast|url=http://allthingscomedy.com/channels/55/all-things-comedy-live-podcast|website=All Things Comedy|publisher=All Things Comedy|accessdate=15 May 2015}}</ref>

